29/03/2011
BAGHDAD, Iraq -- Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan and his Iraqi counterpart Nouri al-Maliki reiterated friendly ties between their countries and pledged further efforts to boost co-operation in various fields.
"Iraq is a brotherly nation," Erdogan said after meeting with al-Maliki in Baghdad on Monday (March 28th).
He noted increasing trade between the two neighbours and mutual efforts to deal with the threat of terrorism.
Al-Maliki said both Iraq and Turkey have suffered attacks from "terrorist operations" but pointed out they are now looking beyond their borders to promote peace and security in the Middle East.
Erdogan is expected make an unprecedented visit to Iraq's northern autonomous Kurdish region, from where rebels of the outlawed Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) have been launching attacks.
(Zaman, Radikal - 29/03/11;
Hurriyet, Anadolu news agency - 28/03/11)
